AGI - "I'm not in an ivory tower", but my thoughts say it in official contexts and not in "informal occasions". Sergio Mattarella> enters the wolf's tan, the citadel of Wisdom where for days the tents of pro-Palestinian students preside over the lawn in front of the rectory to ask that the athenaeus boycott agreements with the universities of Israel. "What do you think of Gaza?" ask the boys while the head of the state reads their banner carefully on his arrival. Shortly before the students had scanned a letter to the megaphone in which they asked him to take a clear position on the conflict in the Middle East. The President also chooses this time an institutional seat, as he believes it requires his role, but does not intend to subtract from the comparison of merit, on the contrary points out that what he had to say he said where he competes, and without shyness: to the General Assembly of the UN and in a letter to the President of Israel. It serves the "immediate ceasefire" declares again in the classroom of Wisdom, during a graduate award ceremony. Outside the protesters continue with slogans and music, but without exceeding the limits indicated by safety. The head of the state repeats, with a long list, everything that should be healed in a world where conflicts multiply instead of decreasing. With a precise rule in the head, checkcase written in the Charter: "All that concerns the dignity of persons, of each person, their freedom, the need to respect humanitarian law is indicated in our Constitution and is therefore necessary for the Italian Republic."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
But first of all, the President is trying to make us understand that we do not want to remove the comparison, indeed: "a letter urged me not to lock myself in what was called the 'vory tower' of the Rectorate. Coming up I saw a sign that basically asked me what I think of what happens in Gaza. I don't want to leave this question without answer." And the answer is articulated. As regards <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-16/Israeli-annuncia-message-nuove-truppe-rafah-26416471/"> the Middle East</a> there are two rights which should coexist: "the right to the security of Israel, the rights of the Palestinian people and, among these rights, to have a State in which to recognize itself."
&nbsp;
< blockquote
"It is a question that the international community feels with great concern and not from today. And not only since the murderer of so many unarmed people by Hamas triggered a spiral of frightening violence"
</blockquote
&nbsp;
Moreover, he wants to point out, "what I think about what happens in Gaza I have said publicly, and not in fortuitous or informal circumstances, but on fully meaningful occasions, as in the intervention I made eight days ago at the General Assembly of the United Nations. Or with the letter that, yesterday, I sent for the feast of that republic, to the President of the Republic of Israel, reitering the request of an immediate ceasefire.' But the defence of rights has no boundaries, it is not possible to circumscribe it to the purged territory of Gaza: "This is true in every direction. As for Gaza, as for the Palestinian people, with thousands of victims, with many orphans, with a large number of homeless people. It applies to boys and girls killed and raped while listening to music in a rave, on October 7 in Israel. It's worth thinking about the kids that day." And it still applies to Iranian rapper condemned to hanging, for Mahsa Amini and for the many Iranian girls who have been imprisoned, tortured, often killed, for girls who are forbidden to attend university and even school in Afghanistan."
&nbsp;
I mean, "for our Republic, all human rights violations must be denounced and opposed. All, everywhere, always, because human dignity, the claim of freedom, the condemnation of overwhelming, the refusal of brutal violence do not change value according to the territories, depending on the borders between States, depending on international relations between political parties or movements". As for the merit of the protesters' request, the boycott of agreements with Israeli universities, Mattarella warns against a very precise danger: "Power, the worst, desires that universities in their country be isolated, without relationships or collaborations with universities in other countries, because this condition allows the worst of the powers to control universities, to compress their cultural level, to compress culture and to prevent it from shouting and pushing for freedom." It is the dialogue that helps peace, and in institutions such as in universities dialogue must be double sense, not in a single sense, "without anyone thinking of being able to impose evaluations or decisions but in respect of others opinions, because in this respect freedom lies". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
